Text: When I was 12, my mother and father went to a wedding. Weddings in Volantis last for days, you know. And they left me with my little brother. The second afternoon they were gone was the hottest day in the three-year summer. We couldn't bear to be inside, so we ran down to the Rhoyne. Every child in Volantis was in the Rhoyne that day. The rich, the poor, we were all there. Naked, screaming, racing to the little islands. Drummers were playing for coppers on the east bank. I was treading water, talking to a friend, when I realized I hadn't seen my brother. I called his name. Then I started screaming his name. And then I saw him floating face down. My heart just stopped. I was I dragged him from the water. My friend helped me, I think. I don't even remember. He was so little. Then we pulled him onto the riverbank. And I screamed at him and I shook him. And he was dead. Just dead. A man ran over. He had a fish tattoo on his face. In Volantis, the slaves have tattoos. So you know what they are without having to talk to them. And this man worked on a fishing boat. And he pushed me out of the way. You have to understand, for a slave to push a highborn girl, that's death for the man, a terrible death. But he pushed me out of the way, and he started pressing on my brother's chest again and again and again, until my brother spat out half of the Rhoyne and cried out. And the man cradled his head and told him to be calm. I decided two things that day. I would not waste my years planning dances and masquerades with the other noble ladies. And when I came of age, I would never live in a slave city again. I'm sorry, Your Grace. You told me of your problems and I've blathered on.

Text: So, you're Ned Stark's bastard. Thank you for the gift, Lord of Bones. You can leave us.
Speaker: MANCE

Text: The girl likes you. You like her back, Snow? That why you want to join us?
Speaker: MANCE

Text: Don't panic, boy. This isn't the damned Night's Watch where we make you swear off girls.

Text: This chicken eater you thought was king is Tormund Giantsbane.

Text: Can't believe this pup killed the Halfhand.

Text: He was our enemy and I'm glad he's dead.

Text: He was my brother once. Back when he had a whole hand. What were you doing with him?
Speaker: MANCE

Text: The Lord Commander sent me to the Halfhand for seasoning.

Text: Why?
Speaker: MANCE

Text: He wants me to lead one day.
Speaker: JON SNOW

Text: But here you are, a traitor kneeling before the King-beyond-the-Wall.
Speaker: MANCE

Text: If I'm a traitor, then you are, too.
Speaker: JON SNOW

Text: Why do you want to join us, Jon Snow?
Speaker: MANCE

Text: (Hesitates.) I want to be free.
Speaker: JON SNOW

Text: No, I don't think so. I think what you want most of all is to be a hero. I'll ask you one last time ... why do you want to join us?
Speaker: MANCE

Text: We stopped at Craster's Keep on the way north. I saw...
Speaker: JON SNOW

Text: You saw what?
Speaker: MANCE

Text: I saw Craster take his own baby boy and leave it in the woods. I saw what took it.

Text: You're telling me you saw one of them? And why would that make you desert your brothers?

Text: Because when I told the Lord Commander, he already knew. Thousands of years ago, the First Men battled the White Walkers and defeated them. I want to fight for the side that fights for the living. Did I come to the right place?

Text: We'll need to find you a new cloak.

Text: What if you took off that bit there?

Text: Trouble is, I've never had much imagination.

Text: Ser Bronn. Ser Bronn.

Text: I didn't hear that.

Text: What do I want from him? He's my father. Do I need to want something? I'm sure he loves me dearly, as any father loves his child, his baby boy. Yet he hasn't come to visit once since arriving in King's Landing. I lay here, my face split in half, but Father never came.

Text: What?

Text: I'm a pirate.

Text: You're a smuggler.

Text: I sent you here to advise the king. I gave you real power and authority. You chose to spend your days as you always have, bedding harlots and drinking with thieves.

Speaker: TYRION

Text: What do you want, Tyrion?

Text: Why does everyone assume I want something? Can't I simply visit with my beloved father? My beloved father who somehow forgot to visit his wounded son after he fell on the battlefield.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: Maester Pycelle assured me your wounds were not fatal.
Speaker: TYWIN

Text: I organized the defense of this city while you held court in the ruins of Harrenhal. I led the foray when the enemies were at the gate while your grandson, the king, quivered in fear behind the walls. I bled in the mud for our family. And as my reward, I was trundled off to some dark little cell. But what do I want? A little bloody gratitude would be a start.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: Jugglers and singers require applause. You are a Lannister. Do you think I demanded a garland of roses every time I suffered a wound on a battlefield? Hmm? Now, I have seven kingdoms to look after and three of them are in open rebellion. So tell me what you want.
Speaker: TYWIN

Text: I want what is mine by right. Jaime is your eldest son, heir to your lands and titles. But he is a Kingsguard, forbidden from marriage or inheritance. The day Jaime put on the white cloak, he gave up his claim to Casterly Rock. I am your son and lawful heir.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: You want Casterly Rock?
Speaker: TYWIN

Text: It is mine by right.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: ( sighs ) We'll find you accommodations more suited to your name and as a reward for your accomplishments during the battle of Blackwater Bay. And when the time is right, you will be given a position fit for your talents so that you can serve your family and protect our legacy. And if you serve faithfully, you will be rewarded with a suitable wife. And I would let myself be consumed by maggots before mocking the family name and making you heir to Casterly Rock.
Speaker: TYWIN

Text: Why?
Speaker: TYRION

Text: Why? You ask that? You, who killed your mother to come into the world? You are an ill-made, spiteful little creature full of envy, lust, and low cunning. Men's laws give you the right to bear my name and display my colors since I cannot prove that you are not mine. And to teach me humility, the gods have condemned me to watch you waddle about wearing that proud lion that was my father's sigil and his father's before him. But neither gods nor men will ever compel me to let you turn Casterly Rock into your whorehouse. Go, now. Speak no more of your rights to Casterly Rock. Go.

Text: Oh, one more thing. The next whore I catch in your bed I'll hang.
Speaker: TYWIN

Text: Was it me you fought on Blackwater Bay? Did I set your ships ablaze? I wasn't there when the wildfire killed our men by the thousands. I could have saved those men. You would have taken the city, Stannis would now sit upon his rightful throne, and you would stand beside him. But I wasn't there because you convinced your king to leave me behind. Do you hear them screaming? All those burning men in the water crying for their mothers, for their gods for help? Until the moment the Blackwater swallowed them.

Text: My mother's always had a penchant for drama. Facts become less and less important to her as she grows older. Our lives were never truly in danger.

Text: Hunger turns men into beasts. I'm glad House Tyrell has been able to help in this regard. They tell me 100 wagons arrive daily now from the Reach. Wheat, barley, apples. We've had a blessed harvest. And, of course, it's our duty to assist the capital in time of need.

Text: Well, as Ser Loras said, Lady Margaery has done this sort of... charitable work before. I'm sure she knows what she's doing.

Text: As a boy, I travelled with a troupe of actors through the Free Cities. One day in Myr, a certain man made my master an offer too tempting to refuse. I feared the man meant to use me as I'd heard some men used small boys. But what he wanted was far worse. He gave me a potion that made me powerless to move or speak, yet did nothing to dull my senses. With a hooked blade he sliced me, root and stem, chanting all the while. He burned my parts in a brazier. The flames turned blue and I heard a voice answer his call. I still dream of that night. Not of the sorcerer, not of his blade. I dream of the voice from the flames. Was it a god? A demon? A conjuror's trick? I don't know. But the sorcerer called and a voice answered. And ever since that day, I have hated magic and all those who practice it. But you can see why I was eager to aid in your fight against Stannis and his Red Priestess. A symbolic revenge of sorts.

Text: Together we announce a new age of harmony. A holy alliance between the Crown and the Faith.

Text: The crown and the faith are the twin pillars upon which the world rests. Together we will restore the Seven Kingdoms to glory.

Text: What’s happening?

Text: When you attack the Faith, you attack the Crown. Anyone who attacks the Crown is unfit to serve as Lord Commander of the Kingsguard.

Text: I have to answer to the gods.

Text: Not when you’re sitting in that chair.
Speaker: JAIME

Text: The Crown’s decision on this matter is final.

Text: Will I be walking naked in the streets? Or will I spend a few months in the sept dungeons first to teach me about the gods’ mercy?

Text: You have served your house and your king faithfully for many years. And you will continue to do so. But not in this city.

Text: You’ve lost it?

Text: It’s a castle, not a bloody sheep. Presumably you still know where it is. You didn’t lose Riverrun. You let the Blackfish take it from you.

Text: He surprised us. He knows the castle better than anyone.

Text: You did lose the Blackfish after the Red Wedding. You had him right here in this hall and you let him leave. Then when I told you to hunt him down and kill him, you couldn’t find him. That’s what it means to lose something. Now he’s come back and taken Riverrun.
Speaker: WALDER

Text: For 300 years we kissed Tully boots, swore oaths to them and their stinking fish banners. Not again. Riverrun is ours. Take it back.
Speaker: WALDER

Text: We’ve got 10 times as many men as the damn Blackfish.
Speaker: WALDER

Text: The Brotherhood Without Banners is rallying the commoners against us, raiding our supply trains and camps.
Speaker: LOTHAR

Text: If I want excuses, I’ll put her in charge. They’re laughing at us. All across the Riverlands right down to King’s Landing, they’re laughing at us.
Speaker: WALDER

Text: I hear it in my sleep! I’m not dead yet, unfortunately for you. And I’ll not leave this world until they all choke on that laughter. Take that castle back.

Text: He’ll never yield, Father.
Speaker: LOTHAR

Text: Oh, he’ll yield.

Text: You’ll show him the knife you used to kill Robb Stark’s child in his whore mother’s belly, and you’ll show him the knife you used to open his niece’s throat. And you’ll remind him who it was that got married at the Red Wedding in the first place. His nephew.

Text: Cheer up, Lord Edmure. You’re going home.

Text: I’m being sent to deal with the Blackfish. Apparently Walder Frey can’t manage it on his own because he’s 400 years old. Sent me with an army to the Riverlands and a siege that could last months.

Text: BEtter you’re elsewhere at the head of an army than in the sept dungeons.

Text: I’m not going to the Riverlands.

Text: What, then?

Text: I’m going to give Bronn the largest bag of gold anyone’s ever seen and have him gather the best killers he knows. I’ll take them to the sept and I’ll remove the High Sparrow’s head and every other sparrow head I can find.
Speaker: JAIME

Text: You can’t.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: He has our son! He stole our son! He’s torn our family apart. How should we treat people who tear us apart?
Speaker: JAIME

Text: We should treat them without mercy and we will. But if you kill the High Sparrow, you won’t leave the sept alive. And without you, this is all for nothing. Stand at the head of our army where you belong, where Father wanted you. Show our men where their loyalties belong. Show them what lannisters are, what we do to our enemies. And take that stupid little castle back because it’s ours and because you can.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: You’ll stand trial soon. I need to he here for you.
Speaker: JAIME

Text: It will be a trial by combat. I have the Mountain. They’ve made us both stronger, all of them.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: They have no idea how strong we are. No idea what we’re going to do to them.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: We’ve always been together. We’ll always be together. We’re the only two people in the world.

Text: Why did you help us?

Text: The Three-Eyed Raven’s dead.

Text: Who are you?

Text: How?

Text: You are the Three-Eyed Raven now.

Text: You must learn to control it before the Night King comes.
Speaker: BENJEN

Text: Drink.
Speaker: BENJEN

Text: One way or another, he will find his way to the world of men. When he does, you will be there waiting for him. And you will be ready.

Text: Everything all right?

Text: Nobody.
Speaker: DAARIO

Text: Nobody yet.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: So we ride for Meereen and after that we sail for Westeros. What then?

Text: I take what is mine.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: You weren’t made to sit on a chair in a palance.
Speaker: DAARIO

Text: What was I made for?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: You’re a conqueror, Daenerys Stormborn.

Text: Wait here.

Text: I’m going after her. Wait for me here.

Text: Every khal who ever lived chose three blood riders to fight beside him and guard his way. But I am not a khal. I will not choose three blood riders. I choose you all.
Speaker: DAENERYS (speaking Dothraki)

Text: I will ask more of you than any khal has ever asked of his khalassar! Will you ride the wooden horses across the black salt sea?
Speaker: DAENERYS (speaking Dothraki)

Text: Will you kill my enemies in their iron suits and tear down their stone houses?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Will you give me the Seven Kingdoms, the gift Khal Drogo promised me before the Mother of Mountains?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Are you with me?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Now and always?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Up she goes.
Speaker: RAY

Text: Hey, come on. Put your back into it, huh?
Speaker: RAY

Text: Here you are, son.
Speaker: RAY

Text: Oh, gentlemen, please.
Speaker: RAY

Text: In all my days I’ve never seen a man swing an ax like that. How many men did it take to cut you down?
Speaker: RAY

Text: Ooh. he must have been some kind of monster.
Speaker: RAY

Text: I think some of the men are a bit afraid of you.
Speaker: RAY

Text: When I found you, I thought you’d been dead for days. The way you were stinking already and you had bugs all over you and bone was coming through right there.
Speaker: RAY

Text: I was gonna give you a proper burial and then you coughed. Oh, nearly shit myself. I reckoned you were gonna die by the time I loaded you on the wagon, but you didn’t. Now, I reckoned you’d die a dozen more times over the next few days, but you didn’t. What kept you going?
Speaker: RAY

Text: No, there’s a reason you’re still here.
Speaker: RAY

Text: No, a reason. Gods aren’t done with you yet.
Speaker: RAY

Text: Well, maybe he was right. I don’t know much about the gods.
Speaker: RAY

Text: Oh, there’s plenty of pious sons of bitches who think they know the word of god or gods. I don’t. I don’t even know their real names. Maybe it is the Seven. Or maybe it’s the old gods. Or maybe it’s the Lord of Light. Or maybe they’re all the same fucking thing. I don’t know. What matters, I believe, is that there’s something greater than us. And whatever it is, it’s got plans for Sandor Clegane.
Speaker: RAY

Text: I’ve heard stories.
Speaker: RAY

Text: They have.
Speaker: RAY

Text: Your Grace. What are we reading today?
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: The Book of the Mother, Your Holiness. Chapter three, verse 12.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: “Smoothing what was jagged, so does a woman’s love calm a man’s brute nature. A wife salves her husband’s wounds, a mother sings her son to sleep.”
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: You learn quickly. There are some who know every verse of the sacred text, but don’t have a drop of the Mother’s mercy in their blood and savages who can’t read at all who understand the Father’s wisdom.
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: For year I pretended to love the poor, the afflicted. I had pity for them, but I never loved them. They disgusted me.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: They are hard to love.
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: The poor disgust us because they are us, shorn of our illusions. They show us what we’d look like without our fine clothes. How’d we smell without perfume.
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: Can I ask you about a personal matter?
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: Of course.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: The king mentioned that since your reunion, you haven’t joined him in the marriage bed.
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: No.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: You have a duty, Your Grace. To your husband, your king, your country, to the gods themselves.
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: It’s just...the desires that once drove me no longer do.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: Congress does not require desire on the woman’s part, only patience. The king must have an heir if we are to continue our good work.
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: Forgive me. Sometimes the truth path is hard to find.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: Hard to find and harder still to walk upon. But you’ve made great progress. I only pray your grandmother follows your lead.
Speaker: HIGH SPARROW

Text: My grandmother?
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: Yes. The Queen of Thorns is a remarkable woman, a strong woman, and an unrepentant sinner. You must teach her the new way as she taught you the old. Or I fear for her safety, body and soul.

Text: Does it move or talk? I want to speak with you alone.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: Septa Unella has been my true friend and counselor.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: Oh, this is madness!
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: You’re not in your sanctuary now, my dear. All I have to do is whistle and my men will stroll in here and bash you about...

Text: Grandmother.

Text: ...until I tell them to stop. If I tell them to stop. You could use a good bashing.

Text: Grandmother, please.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: What have they done to you?

Text: You marched against the High Sparrow, against the Faith.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: We marched for you.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: The gods could have punished you and Father, but they didn’t. They showed mercy.

Text: And what about your brother? What mercy did they show him?

Text: Have you lost your mind?
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: ...and live his life as a penitent.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: He is the heir to Highgarden, the future of House Tyrell.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: He can begin again.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: As a mindless fanatic.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: As a free man.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: You will leave for Highgarden today. There is no law that says you must stay here.

Text: I am the queen. It is my duty to serve my husband the king.

Text: But you should leave, Grandmother. Your place is at home.

Text: I will never leave you. Never.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: You must.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: Go home. Find comfort in prayer and good works.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: The Mother watches over us all.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: I’ll see you soon, my dear.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: Seven blessings to you, Grandmother.
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: Shall we pray?
Speaker: MARGAERY

Text: We said we’d fight with you, King Crow, when the time comes and we meant it, but this isn’t what we agreed to. These aren’t White Walkers. This isn’t an army of the dead. This isn’t our find.

Text: If it weren’t for him, none of us would be here. All of you would be meat in the Night King’s army. And I’d be a pile of charred bones just like Mance.

Text: Remember Mance’s camp? It stretched all the way to the horizon. And look at us now. Look what’s left of us. And if we lose this, we’re gone. Dozens of tribes, hundreds of generations. Be like we were never there at all. We’ll be the last of the free folk.

Text: That’s what’ll happen to you if we lose. The Boltons, the Karstarks, the Umbers, they know you’re here. They know that more than half of you are women and children. After they finish with me, they’ll come for you. You’re right. This isn’t your fight. You shouldn’t have to come to Winterfell with me. I shouldn’t be asking you. It’s not the deal we made. I need you with me if we’re gonna beat them, and we need to beat them if you’re going to survive.

Text: The crows killed him because he spoke for the free folk when no other southerners would. He died for us. If we are not willing to do the same for him, we’re cowards. And if that’s what we are, we deserve to be the last of the free folk.

Text: Snow.
Speaker: WUN WUN

Text: Are you sure they’ll come?
Speaker: JON SNOW (to TORMUND)

Text: We’re not clever like you southerners. When we say we’ll do something, we do it.

Text: I heard you were leaving King’s Landing.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: That is hardly your concern.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: Your grandson is still a prisoner. You’ll leave him rotting in a cell?

Text: Loras rots in a cell because of you. THe High Sparrow rules this city because of you. Our two ancient houses face collapse because of you and your stupidity.

Text: You’re right. I made a terrible mistake. I carry it with me every single day.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: Good.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: I delivered an army of fanatics onto our doorstep. And now we must fight them together. We need each other.

Text: I wonder if you’re the worst person I’ve ever met. At a certain age, it’s hard to recall. But the truly vile do stand out through the years. Do you remember the way you smirked at me when my grandson and granddaughter were dragged off to their cells? I do. I’ll never forget it.
Speaker: OLENNA

Text: You love your granddaughter. I love my son. It’s the only truth I know. We must defend them.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: I’m leaving this wretched city as fast as I can before that shoeless zealot throws me into one of his cells. If you’re half as bright as you think you are, you’ll find your way out of here, too.

Text: Never. I’ll never leave my son.

Text: What’ll you do, then? You have no support. Not anymore. Your brother’s gone. The High Sparrow saw to that. The rest of your family have abandoned you. The people despise you. You’re surrounded by enemies, thousands of them. You’re going to kill them all by yourself? You’ve lost, Cersei. It’s the only joy I can find in all this misery.

Text: Now, that is a sorry attempt at a siege. Someone needs to teach those sad twats how to dig trenches.

Text: You promised me a lordship and a castle and a highborn beauty for a wife.

Text: Lady Mormont.
Speaker: JON SNOW

Text: Welcome to Bear Island.

Text: I remember when you were born, my lady. You were named for my Aunt Lyanna. It was said she was a great beauty. I’m sure you will be, too.

Text: I doubt it. My mother wasn’t a great beauty or any other kind of beauty. She was a great warrior, though. She died fighting for your brother, Robb.

Text: I think we’ve had enough small talk. What are you here?

Text: I remember what it said. “Bear Island knows no king but the King in the North whose name is Stark.”

Text: Robb is gone, but House Stark is not. And it needs your support now more than ever. I’ve come with my sister to ask for House Mormont’s allegiance.

Text: As far as I understand, you’re a Snow and Lady Sansa is a Bolton. Or is she a Lannister? I’ve heard conflicting reports.

Text: I did what I had to do to survive, my lady. But I am a Stark. I will always be a Stark.

Text: If you say so. In any case, you don’t just want my allegiance. You want my fighting men.

Text: I understand that I’m responsible for Bear Island and all who live here. So why should I sacrifice one more Mormont life for someone else’s war?

Text: If it please, my lady, I understand how you feel.

Text: I don’t know you, Ser…?

Text: Davos, my lady, of House Seaworth.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: You needn’t ask your maester about my house. It’s rather new.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: All right, Ser Davos of House Seaworth. How is it you understand how I feel?
Speaker: LYANNA

Text: You never thought you’d find yourself in your position. Being responsible for so many lives at such a young age. I never thought I’d be in my position. I was a crabber’s son, then I was a smuggler. And now I found myself addressing the lady of a great house in time of war. But I’m here because this isn’t someone else’s war. It’s our war.

Text: Go on, Ser Davos.

Text: Your uncle, Lord Commander Mormont, made that man his steward. He chose Jon to be his successor because he knew had the courage to do what was right, even if it meant giving his life. Because Jeor Mormont and Jon Snow both understood that the real war isn’t between a few squabbling houses. It’s between the living and the dead. And make no mistake, my lady, the dead are coming.

Text: Is this true?

Text: Your uncle fought them at the Fist of the First Men. I fought them at Hardhome. We both lost.

Text: As long as the Boltons hold Winterfell, the North is divided. And a divided North won’t stand a chance against the Night King. You want to protect your people, my lady. I understand. But there’s no hiding from this. We have to fight and we need to do it together.

Text: House Mormont has kept faith with House Stark for 1,000 years. We will not break faith today.

Text: Thank you, my lady. How many fighting men can we expect?

Text: We are not a large house, but we’re a proud one. And every man from Bear Island fights with the strength of 10 mainlanders.

Text: If they’re half as ferocious as their lady, the Boltons are doomed.

Text: Kingslayer.
Speaker: BRYNDEN

Text: Blackfish.
Speaker: JAIME

Text: I assume you’re here to fulfill the vow you gave my niece. I don’t see Sansa and Arya.

Text: Then why are you here?

Text: Or you’ll kill Edmure?

Text: Aye, now I have. I’m disappointed.

Text: The answer is no.

Text: Yes, my family served House Stark for centuries. We wept when we heard of your father’s death. When my brother was lord of this castle, he answered Robb’s call and hailed him King in the North.

Text: And where was King Robb when the Ironborn attacked this castle? When they threw my wife and children in prison and brutalized and killed our subjects? Taking up with a foreign whore. Getting himself and those who followed him killed.

Text: I served House Stark once, but House Stark is dead.
Speaker: ROBETT

Text: Why did we have to come here?

Text: I don’t want one.

Text: Strange.  You spoke so highly of Jon Snow but when he arrives you hide on a cliff.  I didn't take you for a bashful girl.
Speaker: VARYS

Text: My time whispering in the ears of kings has come to an end.

Text: Oh, I doubt that.  Give us common folk one taste of power we're like the lion who tasted man.  Nothing is ever so sweet again.
Speaker: VARYS

Text: Neither of us is common folk anymore.  I did not part on good terms with the King in the North, or his advisor.

Text: Why?

Speaker: MELISANDRE

Text: So where will you go?
Speaker: VARYS

Text: Volantis.

Text: Good.  If you don't mind my saying, I don't think you should return to Westeros.  I'm not sure you'd be safe here.

Text: I will return, dear spider.  One last time.
Speaker: MELISANDRE

Text: My Lady --

Text: I have to die in this strange country, just like you.

Text: You stand in the presence of Daenerys Stormborn of House Targaryen, rightful heir to the Iron Throne, rightful Queen of the Andals and the First Men, Protector of the Seven Kingdoms, the Mother of Dragons, the Khaleesi of the Great Grass Sea, The Unburnt, The Breaker of Chains.
Speaker: MISSANDEI

Text: This is Jon Snow.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: He's King in the North.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: Thank you for traveling so far, My Lords.  I hope the seas weren't too rough.

Text: The winds were kind, Your Grace.
Speaker: JON

Text: Apologies.  I have a Flea Bottom accent, I know.  But Jon Snow is King in the North, Your Grace.  He's not a lord.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: Forgive me --
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Your Grace, this is Ser Davos Seaworth.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: I wasn't there, Your Grace.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: Forever.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: Forever.  So I assume, My Lord, that you're here to bend the knee.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: I am not.
Speaker: JON

Text: Oh.  Well, that is unfortunate.  You've travelled all this way to break faith with House Targaryen?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Break faith?  Your father burned my grandfather alive.  He burned my uncle alive.  He would have burned the Seven Kingdoms.
Speaker: JON

Text: My father was an evil man.  On behalf of House Targaryen I ask your forgiveness for the crimes he committed against your family.  And I ask you not to judge a daughter by the sins of her father.  Our two houses were allies for centuries.  Those were the best centuries the kingdom's ever known.  Centuries of peace and prosperity with the Targaryens sitting on the Iron Throne and a Stark serving as Warden of the North.  I am the last Targaryen, Jon Snow.  Honor the pledge your ancestor made to mine.  Bend the knee and I will name you Warden of the North.  Together we will save this country from those who would destroy it.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: You're right.  You're not guilty of your father's crime.  And I'm not beholden to my ancestor's vows.
Speaker: JON

Text: Then why are you here?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Because I need your help and you need mine.
Speaker: JON

Text: Did you see three dragons flying overhead when you arrived?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: I did.
Speaker: JON

Text: And did you see the Dothraki, all of whom have sworn to kill for me?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: They're hard to miss.
Speaker: JON

Text: But still, I need your help?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Not to defeat Cersei.  You could storm King's Landing tomorrow and the city would fall.  Hell, we almost took it and we didn't even have dragons.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: Almost.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: But you haven't stormed King's Landing.  Why not?  The only reason I can see is you don't want to kill thousands of innocent people.  It's the fastest way to win the war but you won't do it.  Which means at the very least you're better than Cersei.
Speaker: JON

Text: Still, that doesn't explain why I need your help.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Because right now you and I and Cersei and everyone else, we're children playing at a game screaming that the rules aren't fair.

Text: You told me you liked this man.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: I do.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: In the time since he's met me he's refused to call me queen, he's refused to bow and now he's calling me a child.

Text: I believe he's calling all of us children.  Figure of speech.

Text: I am not your enemy.  The dead are the enemy.
Speaker: JON

Text: The dead?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: Is that another figure of speech?
Speaker: DAENERYS

Speaker: JON

Text: The Army of the Dead?

Text: You don't know me well, My Lord, but do you think I am a liar or a madman?
Speaker: JON

Text: No, I don't think you're either of those things.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: The Army of the Dead is real.  The White Walkers are real.  The Knight King is real.  I've seen them.  If they get past the wall and we're squabbling amongst ourselves --
Speaker: JON

Text: I was born at Dragonstone.  Not that I can remember it.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: We fled before Robert's assassins could find us.  Robert was your father's best friend, no?  I wonder if your father knew his best friend sent assassins to murder a baby girl in her crib.  Not that it matters now of course.  I spent my life in foreign lands.  So many men have tried to kill me.  I don't remember all of their names.  I have been sold like a brood mare.  I have been chained and betrayed, raped and defiled.  Do you know what kept me standing through all those years in exile?  Faith.  Not in any gods.  Not in myths and legends.  In myself.  In Daenerys Targaryen.  The world hadn't seen a dragon in centuries until my children were born.  The Dothraki hadn't crossed the sea.  Any sea.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: They did for me.  I was born to rule the Seven Kingdoms.  And I will.
Speaker: DAENERYS

Text: You'll be ruling over a graveyard if we don't defeat the Night King.
Speaker: JON

Text: The war against my sister has already begun.  You can't expect us to halt hostilities and join you in fighting --
Speaker: TYRION

Text: You don't believe him.  I understand that.  It sounds like nonsense.

Text: But if destiny has brough Daenerys Targaryen back to our shores, it has also made Jon Snow King in the North.  You were the first to bring Dothraki to Westeros.  He was the first to make allies with Wildlings and northmen.  He was named Lord Commander of the Night's Watch.  He was named King in the North.  Not because of his birthright.  He has no birthright.  He's a damn bastard.  All those hard son's of bitches chose him as their leader because they believe in him.
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: All those things you don't believe in, he faced those things.  He fought those things for the good of his people.  He risked his life for his people.  He took a knife in the heart for his people.  He gave his own --
Speaker: DAVOS

Text: If we don't put asside our enmities and band together we will die.  And then it doesn't matter whose skeleton sits on the Iron Throne.

Text: If it doesn't matter you might as well kneel.

Text: Swear your allegiance to Queen Daenerys.  Help her to defeat my sister and together our armies will protect the north.

Text: It takes no time to bend the knee.  Pledge your sword to her cause.

Text: I mean no offense, Your Grace, but I don't know you.  As far as I can tell your claim to the throne rests entirely on your father's name.  And my own father fought to overthrow the Mad King.  The lords of the north placed their trust in me to lead them.  And I will continue to do so as well as I can.

Text: I want you to know I understand.  Even though we're enemies, you and I, I understand the fear that drives you.  I was there that day when Ser Gregor crushed your lover's head.  I close my eyes I can hear the sound of Oberyn's skull breaking.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: The sound of your scream.  I never heard a sound like that.  I thought, that's true love.  Oberyn looked beautiful that day.  He really did.  No one moved like him.  No one had such skill with a spear.  Even Ser Gregor couldn't stop him.  If only he hadn't taunted him.  He could have walked away and left poor Ser Gregor to die.  But that wasn't your lover's way, was it?  Now he's burried somewhere.  And here Ser Gregor is stronger than ever.  That must be difficult for you.  When my daughter was taken from me, my only daughter, well, you can't imagine how that feels unless you've lost a child.  I fed her at my own breast even though they told me to give her to the wet nurse.  I couldn't bear to see her in another woman's arms.  I never got to have a mother.  But Myrcella did.  She was mine and you took her from me.  Why did you do that?

Text: It doesn't matter now.

Speaker: CERSEI

Text: I know, I know, we're not supposed to have favorites.  But still, we're only human.  We love who we love.

Text: I'm sorry.  I can't understand you.  The gag makes it difficult to understand what you're saying.  It must be frustrating.

Text: We all make our choices.  You chose to murder my daughter.  You must have felt powerful after you made that choice.

Text: Do you feel powerful now?  I don't sleep very well, not at all really.  I lie in bed and I stare at the canopy and imagine ways of killing my enemies.  How to destroy Ellaria Sand, the woman who murdered my only daughter.  I thought about having Ser Gregor crush your skull the way he did Oberyn's.  It would be poetic I suppose but fast.  Too fast.

Text: Momma!

You will live to watch your daughter rot, to watch that beautiful face collapse to bone and dust all the while contemplating the choices you've made.

Text: No, thank you.

Text: Condolences and congratulations.  You've become the first ruling queen in the Seven Kingdoms.  That's quite an accomplishment.  The Iron Bank appreciates how you cast off the yoke of superstition freeing the crown from elements that sought to subvert the rule of law.

Speaker: CERSEI

Text: Your wealthiest ally is the Tyrells who are now your enemies.  You're surrounded on all sides by rivals for the throne.
Speaker: TYCHO

Text: And the Iron Bank wants to bet on a winner.
Speaker: CERSEI

Text: We don't make bets.  We invest in endeavors we deem likely to be successful.

Text: That's a fancy way of saying bet.  The war has already begun.  I've drawn first blood.  I decapitated the Dornish snake.  My armada owns the Narrow Sea.

Text: Euron Greyjoy is loyal to me.

Text: From what I gather she considers herself more of a revolutionary that a monarch.  In your experience how do bankers usually fare with revoltionaries?

Text: The Lannisters owe the Iron Bank quite a lot of money but Lannisters always pay their debts.  Do former slaves or Dothraki or dragons?

Text: Your father's daughter indeed.
Speaker: TYCHO

Text: Give me a fortnight.  Stay in King's Landing as my honored guest and when you return to Braavos I swear to you my debt will be paid in full.

Text: I came out here to brood over my failure to predict the Greyjoy attack.  You're making it difficult.  You look a lot better brooding than I do.  You make me feel like I'm failing at brooding over failing.
Speaker: TYRION

Text: I'm a prisoner on this island.

Text: Except to my ship.  They took my ship.

Text: I do actually.

Text: You didn't before.  Grumpkins and snarks you called them.  Do you remember?  You said it was all nonsense.

Text: It was all nonsense.  Everybody knew it.  But then Mormont saw them and you saw them, and I trust the eyes of an honest man more than I trust what everybody knows.

Text: How do I convince people who don't know me that an enemey they don't believe in is coming to kill them all?

Text: Good question.

Text: I know it's a good question.  I'm looking for an answer.

Text: People's minds aren't made for problems that large.  White Walkers, the Night King, Army of the Dead, it's almost a relief to confront a familiar monster like my sister.

Text: I need to help prepare my people for what's coming.  I can't help them from here.  I'd like to leave.

Text: It seems unlikely that you became King in the North by giving up that easily.

Text: Everyone told me to learn from my father's mistakes.  Don't go south.  Don't answer a summons from the Mad King's daughter, a foreign invader.  And here I am.  A northern fool.
Speaker: JON

Text: Children are not their fathers, luckily for all of us.  And sometimes there's more to foreign invaders than northern fools that meets the eye.  Daenerys could have sailed for Westeros long ago but she didn't.  Instead she stayed where she was and saved many people from horrible fates some of whom are on this island with us right now.  While you're our guest here you might consider asking them what they think of the Mad King's daughter.  She protects people from monsters, just as you do.  That's why she came here.  And she's not about to head north to fight an enemy she's never seen on a word of a man she doesn't know after a single meeting.  That's not a reasonable thing to ask.

Text: What do you mean?

Text: I don't remember.

Text: Are you trying to present your own statements as ancient wisdom?

Text: I would never do that...to you.  The reason I believe Jon Snow is because he's here.  All of his advisors would have told him not to come.  I would have told him not to come, yet he's here anyway.  You don't have to believe him.  Let him mine the Dragonglass.  If he's wrong it's worthless.  You didn't even know it was here.  It's nothing to you.  Give him something by giving him nothing.  Take a step toward a more productive relationship with a possible ally.  Keep him occupied while we focus on the task at hand.  Casterly Rock.

Text: What was that Ser Davos said about taking a knife in the heart for his people?  Did you notice that?

Text: You must allow them their flights of fancy.  It's dreary in the north.

Text: Amazing thing to see.

Text: We must prepare for that eventuality.  Every direction the threat comes from, this is the best place to be.  We need to start building up our grain stores with regular shipments from every keep in the north.  If we don't use it by winter's end we'll give it back to them, but if the entire north has to flee to Winterfell there won't be enough time to bring wagonloads of grain with them.

Text: It could be a fortnight before Jon and the allied armies make it to King's Landing. In the meantime, demand Cersei surrender. Offer her her life in exchange for the throne. If there's a chance to avoid the coming slaughter, we should make the effort.

Text: I've served tyrants most of my life. They all talk about destiny.
